:surname>Marshall</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH030328%2F1"><gtr:id>A12182C8-A008-4B48-938F-E1ED9626B496</gtr:id><gtr:title>Projection and estimation of disability for UK districts</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H030328/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Despite the importance of local information on disability, surveys that measure disability type and severity are not reliably available for local areas. Government statistical agencies regularly produce projections of population, households and labour force but they do not produce projections of disabled populations. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research proposal tackles this information gap by combining data from the Health Survey for England, the General Household Survey and the Census making three important contributions. &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>It disseminates an innovative methodology for the local estimation and projection of age-specific curves of disability rates distinguishing disability type (locomotor (mobility), personal care, hearing and sight) and severity (higher/lower). &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>The proposal provides analysis of the projections that will contribute to debates on the challenges of population ageing and health inequalities in the UK. In each UK district the projected change in the population with a disability is divided into three components linked to changes in population size, population age structure and to disability rates. &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Knowledge will be transferred to non-academic audiences by developing the POPGROUP software and the in-house capabilities of local authority research departments enabling them to replicate and develop the disability estimates and projections produced within this research proposal. &lt;br />&lt;/li>
